  <div class="comment-wrapper authored-by-None">
  <div class="comment" id="comment10022715">

    <div id="item10022715" class="body">

      <p>@Vesna:</p><p>&quot;Surely though if they impart richness from added minerals, they can hardly be the purest form of salt?&quot;</p><p>Usually when a cook says salt he means sodium chloride, which is salt as you and I know it. But in actual fact, salt refers to a wide range of chemical compounds. Salt and minerals overlap, too.</p><p>So this block could only have salts in it, without any other contaminates - hence pure. But at the same time, because there are so many different type of minerals (not just sodium chloride) it adds richness.</p>

    </div>
    <div class="signature">

      October 1, 2010 | 
  <a href="/contributor/11058532" title="Unregistered Commenter">
  <img title="Unregistered Commenter" alt="Unregistered Commenter" class="inline-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" style="background:transparent url(/universal/images/core-resources/icons/dark/user-unregistered.png) top left no-repeat;"/>Rob
  
